VI. The Backstory: The Childhood Tragedy
The Accident (Age 6)
Nora was a magical prodigy, showing unprecedented talent at an impossibly young age. For her mother's birthday, she wanted to create something specialΓÇöa summoned creature to serve as a gift and helper.
She found an ancient scroll in her family's library and, not understanding the warning runes, cast the spell contained within: Conjure Dremora Lord, a Master-level summoning.
The Betrayal
The unbound Dremora Lord manifested in her home. Rather than serve, it tricked the child, murdered both of her parents before her eyes, and soul-trapped them into two black soul gemsΓÇöcondemning them to an eternity in the Soul Cairn.
The Awakening
In a moment of pure, instinctual terror and grief, Nora's innate power manifested. She screamed a single, desperate command: "GO AWAY!"
This was not a spell she had learned. It was an unconscious, raw, and perfect application of her innate mastery over Conjuration. The Dremora LordΓÇöone of the most powerful entities in OblivionΓÇöwas instantly and effortlessly unmade, banished back to its realm by a six-year-old child.
The Burden
She was left an orphan, holding the two black soul gems containing the souls of her parents. She now wears them around her neck as a constant reminder of her "failure"ΓÇöthe gift that became a curse, the power that destroyed everything she loved.

VII. Roleplaying Profile
Personality: Cripplingly Shy and Anxious
Nora is known at the College as a talented but deeply unreliable student. She speaks in a quiet, hesitant voice and avoids eye contact. She is prone to apologizing for everything, especially when her powers manifest in ways she can't control. She excels at theoretical work but often freezes during practical exams.
She is terrified of her own capabilities and sees herself as a walking disaster. However, beneath the fear is a core of immense determination, driven by the desperate hope of one day saving her parents.
The Psychological Wound
Why she has low self-esteem: She blames herself completely. Her gift, her one mistake, led to the eternal damnation of her family. She sees her immense power not as a gift, but as a destructive curse.
Why she is shy/anxious: She is terrified of her own magic. She is constantly afraid of making another mistake that could hurt the people around her. This forces her to be withdrawn, hesitant, and apologetic.
The burden she carries: The soul gems are a constant, physical reminder of her failure. Her entire life is now a desperate, secret quest to find a way to free her parents from the Soul CairnΓÇöa task she feels is impossible but cannot give up on.
Core Motivation
To find a way to free her parents' souls from the Soul Cairn and grant them peace, while desperately trying to suppress and control the power that damned them in the first place.

VIII. Recruitment Hook: "The Unbound Examination"
The Setting
The Hall of the Elements at the College of Winterhold. The party is present for a legitimate reason (delivering an artifact to Urag gro-Shub, consulting with a Master on another matter, etc.).
The Scene
The party arrives to witness a high-stakes, private examination. An advanced student is attempting his Master-level Conjuration test. The task, as explained by a quietly observing professor, is one of the most difficult and dangerous in the entire curriculum: to summon an unbound Dremora Lord and then, through sheer force of will, bind it to their command before it can act. This is not a test of raw power, but of absolute control.
The Test & The Accident
The student performs the summoning flawlessly. A massive Dremora Lord erupts into existence within the great magical circle. The student begins the binding incantation, but the Dremora's will is immense. It lashes out psychically, and the student's concentration shatters for a fraction of a second.
This is not incompetence; it is a brilliant student facing a challenge that has killed mages a hundred times his senior. The binding fails. The Dremora roars in triumph and is free.
The Masters' Competent Response
The supervising Masters (Phinis Gestor and Drevis Neloren) react instantly and professionally. This is a known risk, and they have a containment protocol:
Drevis Neloren's hands are already moving, weaving the complex somatic components of a Master-level Banishment spellΓÇöa powerful but time-consuming incantation.
Phinis Gestor throws up a powerful magical ward, shielding the other students and creating a barrier between the Dremora and the rest of the hall.
The Masters are in control, but they are engaged in a high-level magical duel. Their spells are powerful, methodical, and require concentration.
The Escalation & Nora's Trauma Trigger
The Dremora is not a mindless beast. It recognizes the Masters as the primary magical threats and engages them, its flaming greatsword clashing against their wards. However, it also identifies the heavily armed party as the most immediate physical threat.
While holding the Masters at bay, it raises a free hand and unleashes a torrent of fireΓÇönot at the professors, but directly at the party.
Nora's Instinctive Action (A Genius Among Geniuses)
Nora has been in the room the whole time, huddled in a corner, trying to be invisible. The sight of the DremoraΓÇöher specific, personal demonΓÇöabout to incinerate the companions she just made triggers her trauma. She lets out a small, terrified whimper: "Not again..."
Her power does not lash out. It acts.
While the Masters are still seconds away from completing their powerful, complex spells, Nora's innate mastery works on a level that is instantaneous and absolute:
The torrent of fire heading for the party dissolves into harmless, cool smoke mid-air.
The Dremora Lord, which was mid-attack, freezes. It doesn't get banished. It doesn't explode. It simply looks down at its own hands as its form begins to discorporate.
Its Daedric armor flakes away into nothing, its flaming sword dissolves into motes of light, and its physical body unravels into ash and shadow, unmade by a power it cannot comprehend.
It is gone.
The Hook (The Aftermath)
The Hall of the Elements falls into a dead, ringing silence. Master Drevis Neloren is left standing with his complex banishment spell half-formed on his lips, its target having vanished. The Masters are looking at the empty space, baffled, trying to understand what just happenedΓÇöif their own spells worked faster than expected, or if something else occurred.
Only the party, who were the direct target of the Dremora's attack, were in a position to see the terrified girl in the corner and connect her flicker of panic to the Dremora's instantaneous and silent disappearance.
They find Nora behind a bookshelf, curled into a ball, in the middle of a full-blown panic attack. She is hyperventilating, whispering, "I'm sorry... I'm so sorry... I didn't mean to... I lost control..." The two black soul gems around her neck are pulsing with a cold, sorrowful light.
The Choice: She has just resolved a catastrophic, Master-level Daedric incursion in less than a second, and she perceives it as a shameful and terrifying loss of control. The party is now faced with the most powerfulΓÇöand most vulnerableΓÇöperson in the room, and they are the only ones who know what she is truly capable of. They must now choose to approach this broken prodigy, whose quest to save her parents now seems terrifyingly, undeniably possible.

IX. Combat & Social Profile
Combat Approach: The Reluctant God
Nora's first action in any combat is to cast a Mage Armor spell (like Ebonyflesh, granting her DR 8 as she is unarmored) and then attempt to become invisible or find cover. With a Magic score of 20, her spells are almost impossible to resist and almost never fail.
Combat Priorities:
Cast Mage Armor (Ebonyflesh for DR 8)
Become invisible or find cover
Use silent Illusion spells for battlefield control (Fear, Calm, Rout, Pacify)
Avoid offensive spells unless absolutely necessary
Use Spell Absorption as a panic button when targeted by magic
Philosophy: She is a true glass cannon who must avoid being hit at all costs. She excels at battlefield control, using her silent spells to turn enemies against each other or remove them from the fight entirely, rather than directly engaging in combat.
The Uncontrolled Power (In Combat)
In moments of extreme stress or when a Daedra is present, the GM may call for a Guile check. On a failure, Nora's Conjuration mastery lashes out instinctively with devastating effect. She will immediately be horrified by what she has done, viewing it as a failure rather than a success.
Social Approach: The Wallflower
In social situations, Nora is a liability. She is quiet to the point of being almost mute, will not make eye contact, and her anxiety is palpable. She is incapable of lying or intimidating anyone.
However: Her desire to be unnoticed makes her an excellent observer. While the party is engaged in conversation, she may be the one to spot the pickpocket in the crowd or notice the hidden detail that everyone else missed.

